Around the U.S., parking lots are being set aside for homeless people.

Dozens of lots have opened in the past five years, with new ones being announced every few months, catering to people who can afford a car but not rent. They are sprinkled across the Midwest, reaching as far east as Pennsylvania and North Carolina, and dotting the spine of the Pacific Northwest, providing a safe harbor for a growing cohort of working Americans who are wedged in the unforgiving middle: They earn too little to afford rent but too much to receive government assistance, and have turned their cars into a form of affordable housing. In many cities, the ‚Äúmobile homeless‚Äù now make up a majority of the homeless population.

@callimachir, a Times journalist, and @fremson, a photographer, spent three days documenting a woman living out of her car in Kirkland, Washington. Tap the link in our bio to meet Chrystal Audet, who, despite earning over $72,000 a year, turned to this mobile lifestyle.
